]]\n{{Col-end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Digital One]] (A joint venture with [[GCap Media]] providing UK [[Digital audio broadcasting|DAB]] - wholly owned by Arqiva since 11 February 2008)\n* [[2RN (RT\u00c9 Networks)|2RN]] in [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n* [[Freeview (UK)|Freeview]]\n* [[VT Communications]] (Formerly Merlin Communications, formed from privatisation of [[BBC World Service]] transmitter sites.)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n* Pawley, Edward (1972). ''BBC Engineering 1922\u20131972''. London, BBC. {{ISBN|0-563-12127-0}}\n* Shacklady, Norman and Ellen, Martin (2003). ''On Air: A History of BBC Transmission''. Wavechange Books. {{ISBN|0-9544077-1-7}} (paperback) {{ISBN|0-9544077-0-9}} (hardback).\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|https://www.arqiva.com}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101115094452/http://arqiva.com/broadcast/ Arqiva Online Virtual Tour]\n\n{{Telecommunications industry in the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies of the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British telecommunications and broadcast infrastructure company}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2011}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Arqiva\n| logo = Arqiva Logo.svg\n| logo_size = 200px\n| type = Private\n| foundation = 2005\n| location_city = [[Winchester]], [[England]]\n| location_country = [[United Kingdom]]\n| industry = [[Telecommunication]]s\n| products = \n| services = [[Transmission (telecommunications)|Transmissions]]\n| owner = {{Unbulleted list|[[Canada Pension Plan]] (48%)|[[Macquarie Group]] (25%)|[[IFM Investors]] (14.8%)}}\n| parent = \n| homepage = {{URL|https://www.arqiva.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Arqiva''' {{IPAc-en|\u0251r|\u02c8|k|i\u02d0|v|\u0259}} is a British [[telecommunication]]s company which provides [[infrastructure]] and [[broadcasting|broadcast]] [[transmission (telecommunications)|transmission]] facilities in the [[United Kingdom]] and the Republic of  [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]], along with commercial WiFi<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arqiva.com/wifi/|title=Specialists in WiFi services for businesses|accessdate=2016-03-16}}</ref> and [[smart meter]] facilities for Scotland and the north of England.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/energy/10243513/O2-and-Arqiva-win-2.1bn-smart-meter-contracts.html|title=O2 and Arqiva win \u00a32.1bn smart meter contracts\n|accessdate=2016-03-16}}</ref> The company headquarters is located at Crawley Court in the village of [[Crawley, Hampshire]], just outside [[Winchester]]. Its main customers are broadcasters and mobile phone network operators, and its main asset is a network of circa. 1,500 radio and television transmission sites<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arqiva.com/about-us/at-a-glance.html|title=Arqiva at a glance - Connecting people and organisations|website=Arqiva|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>. It is owned by a consortium of investors led by CPP ([[Canada Pension Plan]]) and the Australian investment house [[Macquarie Group|Macquarie Bank]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arqiva.com/corporate/structure/|title=Corporate Structure|accessdate=2009-04-23}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arqiva.com/about-us/our-shareholders.html|title=Our Shareholders|website=Arqiva|access-date=2019-10-03}}</ref>Arqiva is a patron of The [[Radio Academy]].<ref>The Radio Academy [http://www.radioacademy.org/about/patrons/ \"Patrons\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100107234239/http://www.radioacademy.org/about/patrons/ |date=January 7, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nThrough its NOW Digital subsidiary, it operates various local [[digital radio in the United Kingdom|digital radio ensembles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.localdigitalradio.co.uk/info.php|title=NOW Digital Ltd - Who We Are|accessdate=November 7, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121116022520/http://www.localdigitalradio.co.uk/info.php|archive-date=2012-11-16|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe company, which has a history that dates back to the beginning of regular public broadcasting in the [[United Kingdom]], was actually only formed in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2011/jan/11/john-cresswell-arqiva|title=John Cresswell to head Arqiva|publisher=The Guardian|date=11 January 2001|accessdate=13 September 2015}}</ref> Below is a potted history of the various organisations that are now part of Arqiva:\n\n===British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC)===\nResponsibility for the transmitter assets of the [[BBC]] lay solely within the corporation until 1997. The assets were then split into a separate company, prior to being sold.\n\nThe domestic transmitter network was purchased by a US company, Crown Castle, when it was privatised in 1997. Subsequently, in 2004, this was purchased by [[National Grid plc]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/3846869.stm|title=National Grid buys TV masts firm|date=2004-06-28|access-date=2020-04-17|language=en-GB}}</ref> which merged in its own private communication network, the name changing to National Grid Wireless in October 2005. Transmitters used by the BBC Overseas services were sold to a new startup company, called [[VT Communications|Merlin Communications]].\n\n===National Grid===\n[[National Grid plc]] had a large internal network for the communication of its engineers serving initially the electricity companies, but subsequently, the gas industry as well. This company developed on the back of the growth in mobile phones, and its large portfolio of tower locations. This was added to by the purchase of the former BBC network (as above).\n\nNational Grid Wireless, as it became, led a consortium bidding for the second UK national [[Digital Audio Broadcasting|DAB]] [[Multiplex (TV)|multiplex]] licence, but was unsuccessful. The licence was awarded instead to [[4 Digital Group]] in July 2007.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2007/jul/06/channel4.radio|title=Channel 4 wins radio multiplex bid - MediaGuardian.co.uk|accessdate=2008-01-08 | work=The Guardian | location=London | first=Ben | last=Dowell | date=6 July 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080107171540/http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/2007/jul/06/channel4.radio| archivedate= 7 January 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n===Independent Television Authority (ITA) / Independent Broadcasting Authority (IBA)===\nThe [[Television Act 1954]] gave birth to the [[Independent Television Authority]] (ITA). The ITA appointed and regulated a number of regional programme contractors, and built and operated a network of transmitters.\n\nThe [[Sound Broadcasting Act 1972]] created legal commercial radio in the UK for the first time. It was modelled on ITA, in that programmes were made by local contractors while the regulator, renamed the [[Independent Broadcasting Authority]], owned and operated the transmitters.\n\n===ITC, RA and Transcom===\nThe [[Broadcasting Act 1990]] split the IBA into three bodies. The [[Independent Television Commission]] (ITC) regulated commercial TV and the [[Ofcom|Radio Authority]] (RA) regulated commercial radio. The IBA's engineering division, which operated the transmitters as well as doing research and development, became an independent company called National Transcommunications Limited (NTL), also known as \"Transcom\". At this point, technical standards regulation, previously carried out in accordance with the IBA engineering \"Code of Practice\", seems to have disappeared from the regulatory landscape.\n\n===CableTel, Simoco and NTL===\nTranscom was acquired by International CableTel Inc., which subsequently built its brand around the NTL name. It ran up huge debts during the [[dot-com bubble|dot-com boom]] which crippled the company for many years. In 1998, NTL acquired the UK antenna sites business of Simoco, a [[professional mobile radio|private mobile radio]] (PMR) company formed from Philips Telecom - PMR. In 1999 NTL acquired the UK field service operations business of Simoco. In 2004, NTL sold its 'broadcast unit' to Macquarie Communications Infrastructure Group, but continued as a cable operator.\n\n===Macquarie===\nIn January 2005, [[Macquarie Group|Macquarie Communications Infrastructure Group]] renamed its new subsidiary Arqiva.\nSubsequently in July 2009, Macquarie sold off a substantial part of its holding and moved the remaining amount to its investment fund. Canada Pension Plan Investment Board (CPPIB) now has a 48% holding and Macquarie European Infrastructure Fund 2 (MEIF 2) has 21%, with other [[Macquarie Group]] funds holding 13% <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arqiva.com/corporate/structure/|title=About Us|work=arqiva.com|accessdate=13 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Inmedia===\nArqiva acquired [[Inmedia Communications]] from the Carlyle Group for \u00a368.5 million in July 2005 to form the new Satellite Media Solutions business unit. Inmedia was owned by [[KCOM Group|Kingston Communications]] and known as Kingston inmedia before being bought by the [[Carlyle Group]] in 2004.\n\n===BT Broadcast===\nArqiva announced the signing of a Sale & Purchase Agreement (SPA) with BT to acquire the full-time service components of BT\u2019s Satellite Broadcast Services business for \u00a325 million in cash in November 2006. The deal will include long-term customer contracts, operations and personnel located in the USA, France, Italy and the Netherlands, as well as the UK. Deal completion is subject to regulatory approval in the UK and Germany.\n\n===National Grid Wireless===\nArqiva purchased National Grid Wireless on 3 April 2007 for \u00a32.5billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arqiva.com/press-office/press-releases/press-releases-2007/arqiva-and-national-grid-wireless-combine-to-create-unified-uk-c|title=Arqiva and National Grid Wireless to create unfied UK communications infrastructure - Arqiva.com|accessdate=2007-04-04|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070602105016/http://www.arqiva.com/press-office/press-releases/press-releases-2007/arqiva-and-national-grid-wireless-combine-to-create-unified-uk-c|archivedate=2007-06-02}}</ref> The company planned to run NGW as a separate company \u2013 Macquarie UK Broadcast Ventures Ltd \u2013 pending review of the deal by competition regulators. Regulatory agreement was reached in late 2008 and National Grid Wireless was amalgamated into Arqiva. The new company employs around 2,300 people and operates all the TV and most of the radio transmitters in the UK (BBC national and local and many commercial stations). It is deemed to be a monopoly operator and as such is regulated by [[Ofcom]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/technology-media-telco-SP/idUSL032432220070403|title=Macquarie buys National Grid wireless for $4.9 bln|publisher= Reuters|accessdate= 3 April 2007}}</ref>\n\n===JFMG===\nArqiva purchased PMSE band manager JFMG 19 February 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beirg.co.uk/2009/02/arqiva-buys-jfmg.html|title=BEIRG: Arqiva buys JFMG|work=beirg.co.uk|accessdate=13 September 2015}}</ref> JFMG were contracted by communications regulator [[Ofcom|OFCOM]] to provide spectrum management and licensing services for programme making and special events ([[Programme making and special events|PMSE]]).  In May 2015 Ofcom made the decision to end the contract with Arqiva and to insource the existing services.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jfmg.co.uk/news/ofcom-transition.aspx |title=Ofcom transition }}{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Recent activity==\n\n===OneVision DTT Licence application===\n{{main|One Vision (DTT)}}\n\nDuring 2009, Arqiva were involved in the possibility of provision of digital pay TV in Ireland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/finance/2009/0501/1224245754008.html |title=OneVision wants DTT licence |publisher=[[The Irish Times]] |date=1 May 2009 |accessdate=3 August 2009}}</ref>\n\n===SeeSaw===\n{{main|SeeSaw (Internet television)}}\n\nIn March 2010, Arqiva invested in and launched a catch-up [[Internet television]], [[IPTV]] service called [[SeeSaw (Internet television)|SeeSaw]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/8480815.stm|title=BBC News - Internet TV service Seesaw launches beta trial|work=bbc.co.uk|accessdate=13 September 2015}}</ref>\nSubsequently the holding in the company was reduced to 25%.\n\n===WiFi===\n\nIn July 2012, Arqiva bought Spectrum Interactive, a wholesale only WiFi provider.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.computerweekly.com/news/2240159067/Arqiva-buys-Spectrum-Interactive-to-boost-Wi-Fi-range|title=Arqiva buys Spectrum Interactive to boost Wi-Fi range|accessdate=2016-03-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Arqiva sold its WiFi Business to Virgin Media <ref>{{cite web|url=https://arqivawifi.com/news/press-releases/arqiva-confirms-sale-of-wifi-business-to-virgin-media-and-announces-in-building-solutions-partnership/|title=Arqiva confirms sale of WiFi business to Virgin Media|accessdate=2016-09-08}}</ref>\n\n==Notable transmitter sites==\n{{GeoGroupTemplate}}\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-break}}\n* [[Alexandra Palace television station|Alexandra Palace]]({{coord|51|35|40|N|0|7|45|W|type:landmark_region:GB}})\n* [[Angus transmitting station|Angus]]({{coord|56|33|18|N|2|59|10|W|type:landmark_region:GB}})\n* [[Arfon transmitting station|Arfon]] ({{coord|53|1|11|N|4|16|24|W|type:landmark_region:GB}})\n* [[Ashkirk transmitting station|Ashkirk]] ({{coord|55|30|39|N|2|50|26|W|type:landmark_region:GB}})\n* [[Ashton Moss transmitting stations|Ashton Moss]] ({{coord|53|28|59|N|2|7|43|W|name=Ashton Moss West MF station}} & {{coord|53|29|28|N|2|6|55|W|name=Ashton Moss East MF station}})\n* [[Beacon Hill transmitting station|Beacon Hill]] ({{coord|50|26|47|N|3|36|39|W|name=Beacon Hill A}} & {{coord|50|26|49|N|3|36|37|W|name=Beacon Hill b}})\n* [[Belmont transmitting station|Belmont]] ({{coord|53|20|9|N|0|10|19|W|type:landmark_region:GB}})\n* [[Black Hill transmitting station|Black Hill]]\n* [[Black Mountain transmitting station|Black Mountain]]\n* [[Bilsdale transmitting station|Bilsdale West Moor]]\n* [[Blaenplwyf transmitting station|Blaenplwyf]] ({{coord|52|21|38|N|4|6|10|W|type:landmark_region:GB}})\n* [[Bluebell Hill transmitting station|Bluebell Hill]] ({{coord|51|19|27|N|0|31|14|E|type:landmark_region:GB}})\n* [[Bressay transmitting station|Bressay]]\n* [[Brookmans Park transmitting station|Brookmans Park]]\n* [[Brougher Mountain transmitting station|Brougher Mountain]] ({{coord|54|25|24|N|7|27|45|W|type:landmark_region:GB}})\n* [[Burghead transmitting station|Burghead]]\n* [[Burnhope transmitting station|Burnhope]]\n* [[Caldbeck transmitting station|Caldbeck]]\n* [[Caradon Hill transmitting station|Caradon Hill]]\n* [[Carmel transmitting station|Carmel]] ({{coord|51|49|6.5|N|4|3|58|W|type:landmark_region:GB}})\n* [[Chatton transmitting station|Chatton]] ({{coord|55|31|55|N|1|50|3|W|type:landmark_region:GB}})\n* [[Chillerton Down transmitting station|Chillerton Down]]\n* [[Clevedon transmitting station|Clevedon]] ({{coord|51|25|24|N|2|51|52|W|type:landmark_region:GB}})\n* [[Craigkelly transmitting station|Craigkelly]]\n* [[Croydon transmitting station|Croydon]]\n* [[Crystal Palace transmitting station|Crystal Palace]] ({{coord|54|49|19|N|1|42|53|W|type:landmark_region:GB}})\n* [[Darvel transmitting station|Darvel]] ({{coord|55|34|46|N|4|17|23|W|type:landmark_region:GB}})\n* [[Daventry transmitting station|Daventry]]\n* [[Divis transmitting station|Divis]]\n* [[Douglas transmitting station|Douglas]] ({{coord|54|8|26|N|4|29|35|W|type:landmark_region:IM}})\n* [[Dover transmitting station|Dover]]\n* [[Droitwich transmitting station|Droitwich]]\n* [[Durris transmitting station|Durris]] ({{coord|56|59|59|N|2|23|30|W|type:landmark_region:GB}})\n{{Col-break}}\n* [[Eitshal transmitting station|Eitshal]] ({{coord|58|10|45|N|6|35|6|W|type:landmark_region:GB}})\n* [[Emley Moor transmitting station